                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d388">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Paris Peace Conference 180.03401/32</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Notes of a Meeting held at President <persName
                            corresp="#p_WW1">Wilson</persName>’s House in the Place des Etats-Unis,
                        Paris, on Monday, May 26th, 1919, at 11 a.m.</hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Paris</placeName>, <date
                        ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1919-05-26T11:00:00+01:00">May 26, 1919, 11 a.m.</date>
                </dateline>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extracts]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p rend="right">C. F. 32</p>
                <list type="participants">
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Present</hi>.—<hi rend="italic">United States of
                            America</hi>. President <persName corresp="#p_WW1"
                            >Wilson</persName>.—<hi rend="italic">British Empire</hi>. The Rt. Hon.
                            <persName corresp="#p_LGD1">D. Lloyd George</persName>, M.P.—<hi
                            rend="italic">France</hi>. M. <persName corresp="#p_CGEB1"
                            >Clemenceau</persName>.—<hi rend="italic">Italy</hi>. H. E. M. <persName
                            corresp="#p_OVE1">Orlando</persName>.</item>
                </list>
                <table cols="3" rend="width: 70%;" rendition="#center-block" rows="3">
                    <row>
                        <cell>Sir <persName corresp="#p_HLCSM1">Maurice Hankey</persName>,
                            K.C.B.</cell>
                        <cell role="brace" rows="2">}</cell>
                        <cell rows="2">
                            <hi rend="italic">Secretaries.</hi>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>
                            <persName corresp="#p_MDJACC1">Count Aldrovandi</persName>.</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Prof. <persName>P. J. Mantoux</persName>.</cell>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>
                            <hi rend="italic">Interpreter.</hi>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                <p rend="center">Russia: Policy of Allied &amp; Associated Powers</p>
                <p>3. With reference to C. F. 31, Minute 1, <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir <persName
                            corresp="#p_HLCSM1">Maurice Hankey</persName>
                    </hi> stated that the Japanese Delegation had agreed to the draft despatch to
                        <persName corresp="#p_KAAV1">Admiral Koltchak</persName> (Appendix
                        III),<note n="89" xml:id="d388fn89">Not printed. For final draft, See <ref
                            target="#pg_367">p. 367</ref>.</note> subject to two very small
                    amendments, namely, in paragraph 2 instead of the words “they are now being
                    pressed to withdraw etc.,” was substituted the following: “some of the Allied
                    and Associated Governments are now being pressed to withdraw etc.,” and
                    paragraph 4 instead of the words “the last year” was substituted “the last 12
                    months.”</p>
                <p>(These alterations were approved and the letter was signed by the Four Heads of
                    States. The letter was then taken by Mr. <persName>Philip Kerr</persName> to the
                    Japanese Embassy, where it was signed by the <persName corresp="#p_SM1">Marquis
                        Saionji</persName>. Sir <persName corresp="#p_HLCSM1">Maurice
                        Hankey</persName> was instructed to communicate the letter to the
                    Secretary-General with instructions to despatch it, in the name of the
                    Conference to <persName corresp="#p_KAAV1">Admiral Koltchak</persName>.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Note</hi>. The <persName corresp="#p_SM1">Marquis
                        Saionji</persName>, when appending his signature, particularly asked that
                    the letter should not be published until a reply was received. Sir <persName
                        corresp="#p_HLCSM1">Maurice Hankey</persName> made a communication in this
                    sense to the Secretary-General.)</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
            </div>
